  <section*|Finite Representation of Eigenfunctions>

  When the orthonormal basis is specifically derived from the kernel of a
  Gaussian process to form its reproducing kernel Hilbert space (RKHS),
  eigenfunctions <math|\<psi\><rsub|k><around|(|x|)>> of the covariance
  kernel can be exactly represented as finite linear combinations of this
  basis. This is a unique circumstance, distinct from scenarios involving an
  arbitrary orthogonal set that does not necessarily converge to the kernel
  function. Under these conditions, the exact representation is:

  <\equation>
    \<psi\><rsub|k><around|(|x|)>=<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|k>c<rsub|k,n>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>,
  </equation>

  where \ <math|<around|{|\<phi\><rsub|n>|}><rsub|n=0><rsup|k>> \ denotes the
  orthogonal polynomials derived from the kernel, and <math|ck,n> are the
  coefficients for the linear combination.

  <section*|Integral Covariance Equation to Sturm-Liouville Form>

  Given the integral covariance equation for a Gaussian process:

  <\equation>
    <big|int>R<around|(|x,y|)>*\<psi\><rsub|k><around|(|y|)>*d*y=\<lambda\><rsub|k>*\<psi\><rsub|k><around|(|x|)>
  </equation>

  and substituting the finite representation of
  <math|\<psi\><rsub|k><around|(|x|)>> results in:

  <\equation>
    <big|int>R<around|(|x,y|)><around*|(|<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|k>c<rsub|k,n>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)>*d*y=\<lambda\><rsub|k>*<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|k>c<rsub|k,n>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>
  </equation>

  Differentiating both sides of this equation twice with respect to <math|x>,
  under the assumption that <math|R<around|(|x,y|)>> is sufficiently smooth,
  aligns this problem with the structure of a Sturm-Liouville differential
  equation:

  <\equation>
    \<lambda\><rsub|k>*<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|k>c<rsub|k,n>*<frac|d<rsup|2>|d*x<rsup|2>>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|k>c<rsub|k,n>*<big|int><frac|d<rsup|2>|d*x<rsup|2>>*R<around|(|x,y|)>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>*d*y
  </equation>

  <section*|Application of Leibniz's Rule>

  Leibniz's rule, which allows for the exchange of differentiation and
  integration under certain regularity conditions on
  <math|R<around|(|x,y|)>>, is applied as follows:

  <\equation>
    <frac|d<rsup|2>|d*x<rsup|2>>*<big|int>R<around|(|x,y|)>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>*d*y=<big|int><frac|d<rsup|2>|d*x<rsup|2>>*R<around|(|x,y|)>*\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>*d*y,
  </equation>

  facilitating the transformation of the integral covariance equation into a
  differential form that closely resembles the Sturm-Liouville problem.

  <section*|Triangular System and Back-Substitution>

  This transformation implies a system of linear equations for the
  coefficients <math|c<rsub|k,n>>, with the system's structure being
  triangular when expressed in matrix form due to the orthogonality and
  completeness of the basis <math|\<phi\><rsub|n>>. The general form of this
  system is:

  <\equation>
    <math-bf|A><rsub|k><math-bf|c><rsub|k>=\<lambda\><rsub|k><math-bf|B><rsub|k><math-bf|c><rsub|k>,
  </equation>

  where <math|<math-bf|A><rsub|k>> and <math|<math-bf|B><rsub|k>> represent
  matrices derived from the differential operations and the integral terms,
  respectively, and <math|<math-bf|c>k> denotes the vector of coefficients
  <math|ck,n>. The solution for <math|<math-bf|c><rsub|k>> is achieved
  through back-substitution, provided <math|<math-bf|A><rsub|k>> is
  invertible.

  <section*|Matrix Definitions and Solution Formula>

  The matrices are defined as follows:

  <math|<math-bf|A><rsub|k><around|[|n,m|]>=<around|\<langle\>|<frac|d<rsup|2>|d*x<rsup|2>>*\<phi\><rsub|n>,\<phi\><rsub|m>|\<rangle\>>>,
  representing the action of the second derivative on the basis functions.
  <math|<math-bf|B><rsub|k><around|[|n,m|]>=<big|int>\<phi\><rsub|n><around|(|y|)><around*|(|<big|int><frac|d<rsup|2>|d*x<rsup|2>>*R<around|(|x,y|)>*\<phi\><rsub|m><around|(|x|)>*d*x|)>*d*y>,
  accounting for the kernel's second derivative and the basis functions.

  The solution for <math|<math-bf|c><rsub|k>> is found by solving the linear
  system:

  <\equation>
    <math-bf|c><rsub|k>=<math-bf|A><rsub|k><rsup|-1>\<lambda\><rsub|k><math-bf|B><rsub|k><math-bf|c><rsub|k>,
  </equation>

  where <math|<math-bf|A><rsub|k><rsup|-1>> is the inverse of
  <math|<math-bf|A><rsub|k>>. Eigenvalues <math|\<lambda\><rsub|k>> are
  determined by ensuring the determinant of
  <math|<around|(|<math-bf|A><rsub|k>-\<lambda\><rsub|k><math-bf|B><rsub|k>|)>>
  equals zero, a condition for non-trivial solutions.
